article.description:
Tangela Smith led four Sacramento players in double
figures with 18 points, helping the Monarchs beat the Miami Sol 78-62 Wednesday for their first win in 11 road games.
article.headline: Monarchs end Sol's four-game win streak
article.linkText: Smith leads Monarchs to first win in 11 road games
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Tangela Smith scored 18 points, one of four Monarchs to score in double figures, and Sacramento beat Miami 78-62 Wednesday, snapping the Sol's four-game winning streak. Kedra Holland-Corn scored 17 points, Yolanda Griffith had 14 and reserve Ruthie Bolton added 13 as Sacramento (4-15) prevented the Sol (9-11) from reaching .500 for the first time this season. Miami had won seven of eight games before the All-Star break. Smith and Griffith also combined for 17 rebounds. The 78 points is the most Miami has given up all season and it was the first road win of the year for the Monarchs ending an 0-10 streak. "I have a lot of respect for my team because they never really gave up,'' Monarchs coach Maura McHugh said. "Even when we were down and struggling, we never had bad attitudes or that 'throw in the towel' mentality. Now we look at the break as a new season for us. We're going to try and take care of business the rest of the season.'' Betty Lennox had 18 points for Miami, while Sandy Brondello added 10. "We came out sluggish,'' Lennox said. "We didn't play defense and they took advantage of that.'' Sacramento controlled the game from the beginning. Down by seven at halftime, Miami never made a game of it in the second half as the lead ballooned to as many as 22 points. The Monarchs often went right to the basket for easy layups as Miami's defense had numerous breakdowns. "We did a pretty good job of establishing the inside game to start,'' McHugh said. "Later that gave us a lot of outside opportunities. We shot the ball better today. We got a lot of transition baskets too. Making layups helps.'' The Monarchs, who like the Sol began the season 2-9, which entered as the WNBA's worst shooting team from the field (37.8 percent). They outshot Miami for the game 50 percent (30-for-60) to 37.3 percent (22-for-59). "They were on a winning streak,'' Griffith said. "Instead of thinking about how they're playing, we focused on how good we can play. That's the bottom line. We haven't been playing good basketball.'' Last season, Miami went 10-3 after the All-Star break to earn its first playoff berth. "We are a much better team then we showed,'' Brondello said. "Our effort was not there and it showed. Our defense just broke down and it wasn't working.'' Game notes
Most of the franchise record crowd, announced at 15,519 (a sellout), was made up of South Florida children as Miami held its second "Camp Day'' afternoon of the season. ... Miami's Ruth Riley played without a splint on her right hand that she's been wearing to protect the right pinkie she fractured seven weeks ago. ... Sacramento's Yolanda Griffith, who played nearby at Florida Atlantic, had cramps in her right hamstring and left the game briefly in the second half before returning. She only played three games in the first half of the season because of a bulging cervical disc. ... Miami's Sheri Sam struggled to find her touch, missing eight of nine shots.
